Macedonians hold a referendum to decide whether to change the country's name
Last Sunday, the Macedonian people held a referendum on the change of name to “North Macedonia Republic,” a measure that would resolve a decades-old dispute with Greece, which had blocked Macedonia’s requests to join the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, argues that its northern neighbor’s name constitutes a claim to its territory and has vetoed entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not participate in the referendum, and a boycott campaign casts doubt on whether the minimum participation required of 50% will be reached for the referendum to be valid.
The question indicated on the referendum paper is: “Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU, with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to achieve accession of Macedonia, one of the countries created following the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to bodies such as the EU and NATO.
“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely under the auspices of the European Union, because it means that all of us will have a safer life,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of MPs have expressed that they will stick to the result of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority in Parliament is required.
The State Electoral Commission reported that no irregularities had occurred at 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% registered in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered people voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, in Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in the referendum held in Macedonia on the name change of the country, which would open the way for accession to the European Union and NATO in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Skopje Parliament, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents set up by the people who would boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries, like China and Russia, and be part of Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will be accompanied by more than necessary investments in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I think the vast majority will vote in favour, because more than 80% of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
Zaev said that a “yes” would be “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute of Political Research, between 30% and 43% of voters would take part in the referendum, a figure below the minimum required participation.
According to the results of another survey, led by the Macedonian channel Telma TV, 57% of respondents are scheduled to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70% said they would vote yes.
For the referendum to be valid, participation must be 50% plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would be the first hard hit for the pro-Western government's policy since it took off in May last year.
