John Edward: Linguistic skills are essential for global citizens
Independent Schools of Scotland maintain a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Council (SCIS), strive to offer the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher studies, for the career they choose and for their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a very popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will reach his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages lead the ranking tables with the highest ratings in independent schools.
Sixty-eight percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A grade.
The data, collected from 74 member schools of the SCIS reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A grade in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A grade.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons employers gave to it that it was difficult to cover the vacancies were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he/she has learned a second language, he/she will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% did not know a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find an important job.
In Scotland, there is diversity among schools as to the languages being taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are thought to be more important for the UK in the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, you can always choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have teaching staff specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In today’s global trading environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered truly “international communicative skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scottish people.
We have to do it.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
