Harvard students take a course on resting habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of caffeine-stimulated overnight study.
One academic noted that students at the number one university in the world are often distracted by what goes into the basic aspects of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after making a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the conversation, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, all this, in my last year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, implemented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic concepts about how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, of one hour duration, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects lack of sleep, and about the importance of maintaining a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in staying awake all night long still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-growing problem.
Making sure to enjoy good quality sleep for enough time should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in ignition mode and makes students always want to have it.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, according to him, is to ask postgraduate students to perform a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to take into account the fact of putting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circadian rhythm and cause problems.
