The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the web, is launching a new company that aims to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s solid open source platform.
The Solid platform allows users to choose where their data is stored and which people can access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt's hidden intention was to "dominate the world".
“We have to do it now,” he said of the emerging company.
“It’s a historic moment.”
The application uses the technology of the Solid platform to allow users to create their own "personal online data storage" or a POD.
It can contain contact lists, pending task lists, a calendar, a music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify. They’re all available in one browser at a time.
What is exclusive of the personal online data warehouse is that the user is the one who decides who can access certain information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
The idea of Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, is that the company integrate appropriate resources, processes and skills so that the Solid platform is available to everyone.
The company is currently formed by Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform acquired by IBM, some in-house developers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer encoders.
As of this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that none of his team is talking to "Facebook and Google about whether to introduce a radical change where all business models are completely emptied overnight.
“We’re not asking for permission.”
Berners-Lee wrote in a press release Saturday that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new web integrated into the Solid platform.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Even during the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the World Wide Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this new era of the web,” Berners-Lee said.
Bernard Vann: Celebration of the clergy of the Victory Cross of the I GM
The only clergyman in the Church of England who won a Victory Cross during World War I as a fighter has been honored in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel and Reverend Bernard Vann received the award on 29 September 1918 for the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was shot down by a sniper four days later and never knew he had won the most important British military honor.
His two grandchildren unveiled a memorial tombstone at a parade Saturday in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandchildren, Michael Vann, said it was "magnificantly symbolic" that the gravestone was presented exactly 100 years after his grandfather's award-winning achievement.
According to The London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through a very thick fog and under the intense fire of cannons and machine guns."
He later ran towards the line of fire and, with "maximum courage", advanced the line before throwing himself over a single-handed cannon and leaving three members of the detachment atone.
The lieutenant colonel was shot down by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the war was over.
Michael Vann (72) said that his grandfather's actions were a feat he could never equal, which produces a sense of humility.
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also left a crown after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt very honored to be part of the parade and added that the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support he will receive from many people.
