The new warship of Germany, postponed again
The new German Navy frigate should have been completed in 2014 to replace the old Cold War-era warships, but it will not do so until at least next year due to faulty systems and an increase in cost, according to local media.
The completion of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the main ship of the new frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class, has been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which cites a military spokesman.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but post-construction problems have marked the deadlines for this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Württemberg-class ships commissioned by the Navy in 2007 will replace the old Bremen-class frigates.
It is believed that it will include a powerful cannon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-bomb missiles, as well as technology against stealth actions, such as a reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other highlights include longer periods between maintenance: it should be possible to use the new frigates for up to two years without passing through national ports.
However, these continuous delays imply that the avant-garde ships, which were expected to project into Germany as a powerful force abroad, will already be obsolete when they come into operation, according to Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate F125 was already news last year, when the German Navy rejected the ship and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to the builder once it had been delivered.
Few details of the reasons why it was returned are known, but German media have cited several "material and technical defects" of the ship that rendered it useless if used in combat missions.
The technical problems are important, as approximately 120 sailors, half the crew needed for the former Bremen-class frigates, operate on Baden-Württemberg-class ships.
In addition, it has also been known that the ship's weight is excessive, which reduces its performance and limits the Navy's ability to add future improvements.
The 7,000-ton Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to weigh twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Apart from the defective materials, the cost of the project, which includes the training of the crew, also begins to pose a problem.
It is believed to have reached an astonishing <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion ($3.6 billion) from an initial budget of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
The problems of the new frigates have become a matter of particular importance, given recent warnings indicating that Germany's maritime military power is being weakened.
This year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defence committee, has acknowledged that the Navy "is running out of ships that can be used".
The officer said the situation has worsened over time because the old ships were stopped, but no new ones were provided as spares.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Württemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
A new study on a farm in the Highlands of Scotland aims to discover how bats use the landscape to feed.
The findings are expected to provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will follow soprano and common bats, as well as northern ear and water bats in the Inverewe Botanical Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at key locations of the property to track the activities of bats during the season.
Volunteers and staff of the UK National Health Service will also perform mobile surveys with portable detectors.
The analysis of the sound of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a map of the habitat will be created to create a detailed landscape image of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, natural conservation advisor at the National Foundation of Scotland, expects the results to show which habitat areas are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating meadows, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the rest of the UK has declined considerably in the last century.
Building construction and restoration tasks threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do the paper mortars and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as the attacks of domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo locating technique to locate insects and obstacles that interpose in their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the appropriate training, who perform surveys, nest inspections and sometimes rescues in a regular way.
The organization has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave Estate farm, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
The farm's administrator, David Thompson, claims that it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threave, we have a large area for bats,” he says.
"We have old buildings, many old trees and a good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
Notes the importance of checking for bats before doing maintenance tasks on properties, as it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could result in the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, attack them, molest them and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official of the Scottish Foundation for the Conservation of Bats, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
He said: "We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our species, we don't have enough data on their populations."
