Fishing and agriculture are the pillars of the economy of the province of Celebes Central, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
The exploitation of nickel mines is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the coast of the other end of Celebes.
Palu and Donggala have suffered several tsunamis over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's disaster mitigation agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996 there was also a tsunami in western Donggala that killed nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific fire belt and earthquakes are common in Indonesia.
The following are the main earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a major earthquake on the west coast of Indonesia's Ace province, north of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that affected 14 countries and killed 226,000 people on the coast of the Indian Ocean, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of strong earthquakes hit the western coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Thousands of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, and caused a tsunami that devastated the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6 magnitude earthquake shook a pop zone in Padang City, the capital of Western Sumatra Province.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake struck one of the islands of Mentawai off the coast of Sumatra, causing a 10-metre tsunami that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A mild earthquake affected the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh and caused destruction and panic as the population recalled the devastation of the 2004 deadly earthquake and tsunami.
This time, no tsunami occurred, but more than 100 people died because of the buildings that fell.
2018: A series of major earthquakes occurred on the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok that killed more than 500 people, mainly in the north of the island.
