Red tide update: concentrations are reduced to Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern counties of Lee.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average coastal or coastal distance concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, low to high coastal distance concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom or high counties in Manatee County, bottom to medium coastal concentrations in Charlotte County, and bottom to high coastal concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeast Florida.
